00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:52.160
I'm curious if you can give
any examples of brands trying

00:31:52.160 --> 00:31:55.860
to be the culture setter, but
then it ends up backfiring

00:31:55.860 --> 00:31:57.027
and it's worse.

00:31:57.027 --> 00:31:58.860
MARCUS COLLINS: I mean,
unfortunately, there

00:31:58.860 --> 00:32:01.250
are more examples of that
than there are good examples.

00:32:01.250 --> 00:32:04.590
I guess probably the most
ubiquitous one I can think of

00:32:04.590 --> 00:32:08.049
is Pepsi trying to tap
into a cultural moment.

00:32:08.049 --> 00:32:09.590
And they didn't make
it about people,

00:32:09.590 --> 00:32:11.110
they made it about them.

00:32:11.110 --> 00:32:14.000
And it turned into a meme
that was piled on their face.

00:32:14.000 --> 00:32:14.500
Right?

00:32:14.500 --> 00:32:18.310
And really, the issue there
is that those people at Pepsi,

00:32:18.310 --> 00:32:19.610
they weren't dumb.

00:32:19.610 --> 00:32:22.630
Really smart people people,
MBAs from great schools, right?

00:32:22.630 --> 00:32:23.710
Smart people.

00:32:23.710 --> 00:32:26.490
And it wasn't that they were
dumb or completely oblivious,

00:32:26.490 --> 00:32:28.280
they just weren't
close to the culture.

00:32:28.280 --> 00:32:31.480
They didn't understand the
shared beliefs, the artifacts,

00:32:31.480 --> 00:32:33.770
the social norms, the
unwritten rules, the language

00:32:33.770 --> 00:32:34.860
that they use.

00:32:34.860 --> 00:32:38.230
And it's the lack of
understanding the nuances that

00:32:38.230 --> 00:32:39.445
get you out of step.

00:32:39.445 --> 00:32:41.290
If you don't
understand the nuances,

00:32:41.290 --> 00:32:43.060
that's when you play yourself.

00:32:43.060 --> 00:32:45.460
So the idea is to stay
very, very, very, very

00:32:45.460 --> 00:32:46.960
close to the culture.

00:32:46.960 --> 00:32:49.390
If oftentimes requires you
being a part of the culture as

00:32:49.390 --> 00:32:51.320
opposed to being a tourist.

00:32:51.320 --> 00:32:54.110
Back in the day we used to
call the ethnographic studies,

00:32:54.110 --> 00:32:57.200
like getting way, way in.

00:32:57.200 --> 00:32:59.960
AUDIENCE: Marcus, I think I
saw an example like a week ago

00:32:59.960 --> 00:33:02.550
of something you're
talking about with Wendy's.

00:33:02.550 --> 00:33:04.960
Did you see the tweet
that Wendy's sent out

00:33:04.960 --> 00:33:08.350
where they were kind of
dogging the Nebraska coach?

00:33:08.350 --> 00:33:10.390
His name is Frost.

00:33:10.390 --> 00:33:11.730
