00:33:47.200 --> 00:33:49.574
a lot of people are going I'm
going to go eat at Wendy's.

00:33:49.574 --> 00:33:52.270
I just love that they've got
the courage to kind of get out

00:33:52.270 --> 00:33:53.915
there and cause some trouble.

00:33:53.915 --> 00:33:55.540
MARCUS COLLINS: Yeah,
I think Wendy's--

00:33:55.540 --> 00:33:57.623
without being very, very
close to their business--

00:33:57.623 --> 00:34:01.150
I think Wendy's figure they're
number three in this space?

00:34:01.150 --> 00:34:03.310
Why not throw some shots?

00:34:03.310 --> 00:34:05.570
And there entire
strategy at this point

00:34:05.570 --> 00:34:08.120
is pretty much about
controlling everybody else.

00:34:08.120 --> 00:34:09.170
It was control.

00:34:09.170 --> 00:34:09.920
And you know what?

00:34:09.920 --> 00:34:13.090
If feelings get hurt,
come on, laugh it off.

00:34:13.090 --> 00:34:15.400
Considering this is a
part of their ethos now,

00:34:15.400 --> 00:34:18.310
people don't-- maybe unless
you're from Nebraska--

00:34:18.310 --> 00:34:20.192
people have pretty
thick skin when

00:34:20.192 --> 00:34:21.880
it comes to that sort of thing.

00:34:21.880 --> 00:34:24.449
But they are hugging all the
right nuances of the culture

00:34:24.449 --> 00:34:25.239
they're a part of.

00:34:25.239 --> 00:34:27.850
And we see things getting
shared or going viral,

00:34:27.850 --> 00:34:30.460
because people who believe the
same thing that Wendy's does,

00:34:30.460 --> 00:34:32.969
their take on things,
people will share it also.

00:34:32.969 --> 00:34:33.489
Right?

00:34:33.489 --> 00:34:35.080
It's all about community.

00:34:35.080 --> 00:34:37.330
Community is another way of
talking about the cultures

00:34:37.330 --> 00:34:39.880
that we're a part of.

00:34:39.880 --> 00:34:43.630
AUDIENCE: You see a lot of
hype around like YouTube

00:34:43.630 --> 00:34:46.090
collaborations,
Instagram collaborations,

00:34:46.090 --> 00:34:49.429
these kind of integrations
that brands are trying to do.

00:34:49.429 --> 00:34:52.600
I'd be curious to hear your
thoughts on that and whether

00:34:52.600 --> 00:34:55.270
that's actually getting
close to culture

00:34:55.270 --> 00:34:56.774
or if it's sort of counter.

00:34:56.774 --> 00:34:58.940
MARCUS COLLINS: So are you
talking about like as far

00:34:58.940 --> 00:35:01.024
as taking advantage of
a platform to do things?

00:35:01.024 --> 00:35:01.690
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:35:01.690 --> 00:35:04.889
Or more like the collaboration
with the creators

00:35:04.889 --> 00:35:05.680
of those platforms.

00:35:05.680 --> 00:35:06.596
MARCUS COLLINS: Right.

00:35:06.596 --> 00:35:07.296
So I'd say this.

00:35:07.296 --> 00:35:09.420
When we think about the
technology, the technology,

00:35:09.420 --> 00:35:13.150
the zeros and ones, if you
will, the zeros and ones

00:35:13.150 --> 00:35:16.080
are the facilitator of networks.

00:35:16.080 --> 00:35:16.720
Right?

00:35:16.720 --> 00:35:18.345
Things that would
normally be disparate

00:35:18.345 --> 00:35:22.000
are now connecting things to
data that goes from one node

00:35:22.000 --> 00:35:23.530
to the next.

00:35:23.530 --> 00:35:26.310
So rules of the road,
same sort of thing.

00:35:26.310 --> 00:35:28.299
And what we find when
we extrapolate that--

00:35:28.299 --> 00:35:30.340
and I'm only talking about
the network of things,

00:35:30.340 --> 00:35:31.910
the network of
people and things--

00:35:31.910 --> 00:35:34.550
was once a network
of people and people.

00:35:34.550 --> 00:35:37.270
And things like
Instagram, Facebook,

00:35:37.270 --> 00:35:38.710
those social
networking platforms

00:35:38.710 --> 00:35:41.162
are connecting people who
see the world similarly, who

00:35:41.162 --> 00:35:42.370
are homophilically connected.

00:35:42.370 --> 00:35:44.935
That is, they share the
same beliefs, social norms,

00:35:44.935 --> 00:35:46.850
unwritten rules and rituals.

00:35:46.850 --> 00:35:50.320
So then when brands partner
with platforms, technologies,

00:35:50.320 --> 00:35:53.290
who understand the dynamics
of the network, dynamics

00:35:53.290 --> 00:35:57.137
of the culture, they
borrow the proxy.

00:35:57.137 --> 00:35:59.470
They borrow people who know
the culture better than they

00:35:59.470 --> 00:36:01.240
do to get them closer to it.

00:36:01.240 --> 00:36:03.010
That's massively powerful.

00:36:03.010 --> 00:36:04.870
The idea, though, is
that it's always going

00:36:04.870 --> 00:36:06.220
to be an outsource skills.

00:36:06.220 --> 00:36:08.400
It's not in the
capability of the brand.

00:36:08.400 --> 00:36:10.720
Capability is about
repeatability and reliability.

00:36:10.720 --> 00:36:12.550
If I have to outsource
that, then I really

00:36:12.550 --> 00:36:15.820
don't have it, which
is good, because they

00:36:15.820 --> 00:36:19.030
get a couple at bats to
do something powerful.

00:36:19.030 --> 00:36:21.310
But it's a challenge for
them, because it's not really

00:36:21.310 --> 00:36:23.630
inside the ethos of what
the brand is all about.

00:36:23.630 --> 00:36:24.276
AUDIENCE: Sure.

00:36:24.276 --> 00:36:26.275
AUDIENCE: So if you're
not a part of the culture

00:36:26.275 --> 00:36:28.750
that you're trying
to get close to it,

00:36:28.750 --> 00:36:31.870
you can run
ethnographic studies.

00:36:31.870 --> 00:36:35.430
Are there tools that
are available to us?

00:36:35.430 --> 00:36:37.850
I mean I'm actually thinking
of an advertising group

00:36:37.850 --> 00:36:41.170
that I work with who
does aftermarket auto.

00:36:41.170 --> 00:36:45.330
So it's exact opposite gender,
exact different age range,

00:36:45.330 --> 00:36:46.730
different lifestyle entirely.

00:36:46.730 --> 00:36:49.230
And I want to get to know them
a little bit more intimately.

00:36:49.230 --> 00:36:51.965
So do have ideas for
tools we can tap into?

00:36:51.965 --> 00:36:53.090
MARCUS COLLINS: I know one.

00:36:53.090 --> 00:36:53.881
It's called Google.

00:36:53.881 --> 00:36:55.510
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:55.510 --> 00:36:57.297
The thing is this that--

00:36:57.297 --> 00:36:59.130
which is why it's so
important to understand

00:36:59.130 --> 00:37:01.860
the evolving media landscape--

00:37:01.860 --> 00:37:05.710
social listening, search
behavior, viewership behavior.

00:37:05.710 --> 00:37:06.540
We get a sense.

00:37:06.540 --> 00:37:10.080
It's a proxy to what people
do, what they believe,

00:37:10.080 --> 00:37:10.680
where they go.

00:37:10.680 --> 00:37:12.270
They talk about
what they believe.

00:37:12.270 --> 00:37:13.380
We know what they wear.

00:37:13.380 --> 00:37:14.550
We know the artifacts
they don because there

00:37:14.550 --> 00:37:15.570
are pictures of them.

00:37:15.570 --> 00:37:17.610
These things provide a
proxy that we normally

00:37:17.610 --> 00:37:19.830
would have to go live
with the coal miners

00:37:19.830 --> 00:37:21.360
to know what coal miners do.

00:37:21.360 --> 00:37:23.790
Instead, we can see
them from a distance

00:37:23.790 --> 00:37:27.810
in a short sort of burst,
but a large representation

00:37:27.810 --> 00:37:30.540
of the population that we
can pull a sample [INAUDIBLE]

00:37:30.540 --> 00:37:32.621
and say this is a real thing.

00:37:32.621 --> 00:37:33.120
Right?

00:37:33.120 --> 00:37:35.190
And it's not really
defined by demography.

00:37:35.190 --> 00:37:37.750
It's not defined by
psychographics either.

00:37:37.750 --> 00:37:39.300
It's defined by
the beliefs that we

00:37:39.300 --> 00:37:41.460
hold, the behaviors
we subscribe to,

00:37:41.460 --> 00:37:42.940
and the language that we use.

00:37:42.940 --> 00:37:46.140
In tech, like search,
like social listening,

00:37:46.140 --> 00:37:47.730
those things
provide a bird's eye

00:37:47.730 --> 00:37:49.470
view we normally
wouldn't have access

00:37:49.470 --> 00:37:51.300
to without a ton of resources.

00:37:51.300 --> 00:37:52.770
I rely on my--

00:37:52.770 --> 00:37:56.700
my Excalibur of sorts is Google
Trends and Crimson Hexagon.

00:37:56.700 --> 00:38:00.810
I use it for everything to
better understand people.

00:38:00.810 --> 00:38:03.622
I have clients across
a wide spectrum

00:38:03.622 --> 00:38:06.080
who are going after different
cultures, different networks.

00:38:06.080 --> 00:38:09.730
It sort of requires me be able
to code switch between them.

00:38:09.730 --> 00:38:11.160
And I can't do all that.

00:38:11.160 --> 00:38:13.380
I can't be that
close to all of them.

00:38:13.380 --> 00:38:15.300
So I can either
use people who work

00:38:15.300 --> 00:38:17.845
at the agency who are
close to the culture or I

00:38:17.845 --> 00:38:20.791
use some proxy via
technologies available.

00:38:20.791 --> 00:38:22.540
AUDIENCE: With the
social listening tools,

00:38:22.540 --> 00:38:24.500
I assume those are like
paid subscriptions.

00:38:24.500 --> 00:38:28.260
So I'm more thinking we know
the wealth of Google tools

00:38:28.260 --> 00:38:30.656
that we have at our
disposal, are there

00:38:30.656 --> 00:38:31.822
free social listening tools?

00:38:31.822 --> 00:38:32.340
MARCUS COLLINS: Absolutely.

00:38:32.340 --> 00:38:33.449
Twitter Bandsearch.

00:38:33.449 --> 00:38:33.990
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:38:33.990 --> 00:38:34.260
Cool.

00:38:34.260 --> 00:38:35.550
MARCUS COLLINS: Super free.

00:38:35.550 --> 00:38:39.665
It's not as robust as using
Crimson or Google Suite

00:38:39.665 --> 00:38:41.490
or something like
that, but it's free.

00:38:41.490 --> 00:38:44.430
It gives you a nice down and
dirty look at what's going on.

00:38:44.430 --> 00:38:47.130
Super representative
of a sample of people.

00:38:47.130 --> 00:38:47.910
Absolutely.

00:38:47.910 --> 00:38:48.450
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:38:48.450 --> 00:38:49.324
MARCUS COLLINS: Yeah.

00:38:49.324 --> 00:38:50.408
AUDIENCE: My question is--

00:38:50.408 --> 00:38:52.865
I know a lot of people have
seen like the Nike "Just Do It"

00:38:52.865 --> 00:38:53.940
campaign, for example.

00:38:53.940 --> 00:38:56.730
And so I guess my question
is when making a decision

00:38:56.730 --> 00:39:01.050
to launch a campaign like that,
it might be considered-- well,

00:39:01.050 --> 00:39:02.940
might not be considered,
some would consider

00:39:02.940 --> 00:39:06.830
it to be culturally polarizing.

00:39:06.830 --> 00:39:08.760
MARCUS COLLINS: Sure.

00:39:08.760 --> 00:39:10.560
AUDIENCE: How does
a company make--

00:39:10.560 --> 00:39:12.630
what decision making
goes into that.

00:39:12.630 --> 00:39:14.130
MARCUS COLLINS: So
I think it really

00:39:14.130 --> 00:39:15.420
boils down to conviction.

00:39:15.420 --> 00:39:16.430
What do you believe?

00:39:16.430 --> 00:39:18.561
Simon Sinek would
say why do you exist?

00:39:18.561 --> 00:39:20.810
People don't buy what you
did, they buy why you do it.

00:39:20.810 --> 00:39:21.309
Right?

00:39:21.309 --> 00:39:22.910
What do you believe?

00:39:22.910 --> 00:39:24.870
And I think the biggest
opportunity for brands

00:39:24.870 --> 00:39:26.970
are to tap into
networks who share

00:39:26.970 --> 00:39:28.362
the same belief as the brand.

00:39:28.362 --> 00:39:29.820
Because those are
the brands we use

00:39:29.820 --> 00:39:33.070
to communicate this is who I
am, this is how I see the world.

00:39:33.070 --> 00:39:36.810
And conviction by
its very essence

00:39:36.810 --> 00:39:38.436
requires saying no to things.

00:39:38.436 --> 00:39:39.810
It required doing
things that may

00:39:39.810 --> 00:39:43.226
be divisive to people who don't
see the world the way you do.

00:39:43.226 --> 00:39:44.850
And the fact that
Nike was like, no, we

00:39:44.850 --> 00:39:48.310
stand with Kaepernick because
he aligns to our belief system.

00:39:48.310 --> 00:39:51.000
And if you don't rock with that,
then you don't rock with us.

00:39:51.000 --> 00:39:52.230
And those people who
were burning their Nikes

00:39:52.230 --> 00:39:54.771
and saying I'm never going to
buy another pair Nike's, you're

00:39:54.771 --> 00:39:57.220
going to die Nike,
your company sucks.

00:39:57.220 --> 00:39:59.714
Well, the people
who believed what

00:39:59.714 --> 00:40:02.130
Nike believes or would stand
with Kaepernick as well, what

00:40:02.130 --> 00:40:03.030
did they say?

00:40:03.030 --> 00:40:04.540
Give me two pair.

00:40:04.540 --> 00:40:05.040
Right?

00:40:05.040 --> 00:40:05.539
I want more.

00:40:05.539 --> 00:40:07.950
I'm going to buy more,
because this thing is

00:40:07.950 --> 00:40:09.420
a representation of our belief.

00:40:09.420 --> 00:40:16.530
So it's difficult. It is a
simple idea, but it's not easy.

00:40:16.530 --> 00:40:20.100
And we often confuse
simplicity and ease.

00:40:20.100 --> 00:40:22.500
Like losing weight
is a simple idea.

00:40:22.500 --> 00:40:23.905
Don't eat so much and move more.

00:40:23.905 --> 00:40:25.690
Pretty simple.

00:40:25.690 --> 00:40:27.200
And it ain't easy.

00:40:27.200 --> 00:40:28.070
Right?

00:40:28.070 --> 00:40:30.586
And the same thing goes
with convictions for brands.

00:40:30.586 --> 00:40:31.710
What do you really believe?

00:40:31.710 --> 00:40:33.600
If you believe that, will
you stand up for that

00:40:33.600 --> 00:40:35.090
when everyone else
is sitting down?

00:40:35.090 --> 00:40:37.590
When everyone else is against
you, will you stand up for it?

00:40:37.590 --> 00:40:39.840
That is what conviction
is all about.

00:40:39.840 --> 00:40:42.920
And the brands who have very
clear and salient convictions

00:40:42.920 --> 00:40:45.420
not only do people know what
they believe and therefore they

00:40:45.420 --> 00:40:48.420
use those brands, but all their
actions, their communications,

00:40:48.420 --> 00:40:53.565
the people that they hire, those
people come towards the brand.

00:40:53.565 --> 00:40:55.690
That's the idea that brands
should have the vision,

00:40:55.690 --> 00:40:57.356
not just what they
communicate, but also

00:40:57.356 --> 00:40:58.770
within the organization.

00:40:58.770 --> 00:41:01.770
So that people who are a part of
the organization, they believe.

00:41:01.770 --> 00:41:03.330
And they, too,
preach the gospel.

00:41:03.330 --> 00:41:05.210
And they too are
demonstrably representations

00:41:05.210 --> 00:41:08.925
of the brand's conviction.

00:41:08.925 --> 00:41:11.520
AUDIENCE: What happens if a
company does have conviction

00:41:11.520 --> 00:41:16.090
but then people start
doing it as appropriation?

00:41:16.090 --> 00:41:20.010
MARCUS COLLINS: This is about
the nuances of the culture.

00:41:20.010 --> 00:41:22.390
It's a hard one to say.

00:41:22.390 --> 00:41:25.894
When we pay mind to the nuances,
we feel like it's a real thing.

00:41:25.894 --> 00:41:27.685
If you don't know the
nuances, when someone

00:41:27.685 --> 00:41:29.000
is saying they're just
appropriating, like,

00:41:29.000 --> 00:41:30.359
no you don't understand.

00:41:30.359 --> 00:41:32.400
Because the brand has
always been a part of this,

00:41:32.400 --> 00:41:34.358
here are all the
demonstrative representations,

00:41:34.358 --> 00:41:36.780
the evidence that shows this
brand's always been this way.

00:41:36.780 --> 00:41:39.471
So them doing this
is nothing new.

00:41:39.471 --> 00:41:41.970
It's just right in line with
what they've always been about.

00:41:41.970 --> 00:41:43.599
But you got to be about it.

00:41:43.599 --> 00:41:44.390
What did Diddy say?

00:41:44.390 --> 00:41:45.720
Don't talk about, be about it.

00:41:45.720 --> 00:41:46.590
Right?

00:41:46.590 --> 00:41:48.837
Same thing.

00:41:48.837 --> 00:41:49.420
AUDIENCE: Hey.

00:41:49.420 --> 00:41:50.253
MARCUS COLLINS: Hey.

00:41:50.253 --> 00:41:53.300
